        <hl1>Microsoft Breakup: A Serious Mistake</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Laura Ritchie letter suggests consumers fight Microsoft's monopoly by selecting other computer systems (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Microsoft Breakup Is Ordered for Antitrust Violations'' (front page, June 8):</p>
        <p>The proceedings against the Microsoft Corporation have left me with one nagging question: What operating system do Justice Department lawyers use on their computers?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Microsoft Breakup Is Ordered for Antitrust Violations'' (front page, June 8):</p>
        <p>The proceedings against the Microsoft Corporation have left me with one nagging question: What operating system do Justice Department lawyers use on their computers?</p>
        <p>Perhaps the key to eliminating the Microsoft monopoly is simply to explore the other options that exist for computer users. Macintosh comes to mind; I am sure there are others.  Fighting a monopoly through court action is one viable option; fighting it through economic action, however, is an underused alternative.</p>
        <p>LAURA RITCHIE  Tacoma, Wash., June 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
